>hām</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘homestead, home farm’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Norton was born in 1383, in England, his father, John Norton, was 19 and his mother, Lucy Attelex, was 26. He married Elizabeth Hussey in 1405, in Bristol, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1429, in Kent, Kent, England, at the age of 46, and was buried in Faversham, Kent, England."},"et":{"1383–1429":"1383–1429","1385–1470":"1385–1470","1416–1458":"1416–1458","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1415–1489":"1415–1489","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1357–1429":"1357–1429","1385":"1385","1383":"1383","1470":"1470","1415":"1415","1458":"1458","about 1429":"umbes 1429","1357":"1357","1489":"1489","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1364":"1364","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","1405":"1405","1416":"1416","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Wales":"Wales","England":"England","Bristol, England":"Bristol, England","Kent, Kent, England":"Kent, Kent, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1383–1429":"1383–1429","1385–1470":"1385–1470","1416–1458":"1416–1458","1428–Female":"1428–Kuollut","1410–Male":"1410–Kuol